The original manuscripts of the first and third prefaces are in a packet of papers belonging to the Basle University Library, together with a great number of the scholia on Jerome in Erasmus' hand. Resides Erasmus’ autograph for this preface (a) the packet contains also a manuscript copy by Conrad Fonteius (p. 67), which seems from notes and marks on it to have been made for use in the press (13¹). In illustration of the critical standards of the age it may be remarked that even βῙ does not reproduce a with minute fidelity, and that in B² the printers followed the established orthography of their press rather than that of Erasmus as represented by Fonteius. These differences of orthography are, however, too numerous to be shown here in detail. The insignificant variants in the revised edition of 1524-6, vol. iv. pp. 407 and 412 (γ), are doubtless due to the printers. In Chevallon's edition, Paris, 1533-4 (see p. 211), the text of this preface, vol. iv. f. 138 νο, follows the variants of γ.

It is noticeable that the second extract, ll. 63-130, is not found in the first drafts of either a or βῙ, but forms part of a passage inserted later ; clearly after the receipt of Ep. 304, to which it is a reply resembling Ep. 337, and thus (cf. Ep. 337. 1) after the visit to England on which Erasmus determined to dedicate the New Testament to Leo x instead of to Warham.
